# Day 23 - Find Peak Element

## Problem Statement
A peak element is an element that is strictly greater than its neighbors.

Given a 0-indexed integer array `nums`, find a peak element and return its index. If the array contains multiple peaks, return the index of any one of them.

You may assume that `nums[-1] = nums[n] = -∞`, meaning the elements outside the array are considered smaller than any element inside the array.

You must write an algorithm that runs in **O(log n)** time.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    int findPeakElement(vector<int>& nums) {

        int st = 0;
        int end = nums.size() - 1;

        while (st < end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1])
                st = mid + 1;
            else
                end = mid;
        }

        return st;
    }
};



## Time Complexity
**O(log n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(1)**

## Approach
This solution uses **Binary Search** to locate a peak element efficiently. At each iteration, the middle element is compared with its next element. If `nums[mid]` is smaller than `nums[mid + 1]`, it means the array is ascending at that point, so a peak must exist on the right side, and the search continues there. Otherwise, the peak lies on the left side (including the current middle element), so the search space is reduced accordingly. The process continues until both pointers meet, and that index represents a peak element. Since the search space is halved in every iteration, the algorithm runs in **O(log n)** time.
